result.execSummary:
The defendant Phillip James Doucette was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Restitution in the total amount of $89,240.38 plus surcharges for all charged cases and unfiled cases, including the unfiled case in Douglas County ($4,098).
Seek and maintain full time employment.
Undergo cognitive intervention therapy and other counseling as directed by DOC

No contact with all victims, their families or their residences.  No contact with any co-actors, including Cory R. Grande, Gabrielle P. Kiggins, Connie M. Denomie, Derek L. Nelis and Gabriel T. Cook.  Maintain absolute sobriety, consume no alcohol and no drugs, except what is prescribed by a physician and taken only as prescribed. He will not possess any drug paraphernalia and precursors to meth.  Will not be present where alcohol or drugs are being consumed; no bars, liquor stores or parties.  As a convicted felon, prohibited from possessing a firearm.  As convicted felon, prohibited to vote until civil rights restored.

Defendant is to submit DNA sample. Income withholding while in prison and once released from prison at the rate of 50% of wages to be paid to the victims.  Agree to provide truthful testimony in the prosecution of any of his co-actors.
AODA Assessment and follow through on all recommendations of Counselor.
